The control plane in one diagram.

We sketched this back in the first notebook. Now let us name every piece. The control plane runs on one or more nodes, and it is made of a handful of programs that, together, decide what the cluster does.

At the centre sit two things. Et-see-dee, the cluster's source of truth, a key value store holding every object. And the kube ay-pee-eye server, the front door, which is the only thing that ever reads from or writes to et-see-dee, and the only thing every other component and every client talks to.

Around them are the brains. The kube scheduler, which watches for pending pods and binds each one to a node. The kube controller manager, a single binary hosting about thirty separate controllers, each running the observe, compare, act loop you have seen all course. And the cloud controller manager, which integrates with a cloud provider for things like load balancers and node lifecycle.

Out on each node, including the control plane nodes themselves, run the worker side programs. The kube-let, the agent that actually starts containers. Kube proxy, which programs the service networking. And a container runtime, which runs the containers.

The shape to hold in your head is this. Clients talk to the ay-pee-eye server. The ay-pee-eye server persists state in et-see-dee. The scheduler and controllers watch the ay-pee-eye server and drive the cluster toward the desired state. And the kube-let on each node makes the decisions real. Every arrow in that picture passes through the ay-pee-eye server. Nothing goes around it.
